Checking ACF, PACF

# The result of the Augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) test indicates that the pre-intervention data is stationary.
adf_test <- adf.test(data$total_rides[data$service_date < as.Date("2020-03-01")])
## Warning in adf.test(data$total_rides[data$service_date <
## as.Date("2020-03-01")]): p-value smaller than printed p-value
print(adf_test)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  data$total_rides[data$service_date < as.Date("2020-03-01")]
## Dickey-Fuller = -11.335, Lag order = 19, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
acf(data$total_rides[data$service_date < as.Date("2020-03-01")])

pacf(data$total_rides[data$service_date < as.Date("2020-03-01")])

# The residual plot shows that the residuals are fairly well centered around zero, though there is significant variability over time. The density of points around zero and the spread indicates that while the ARIMA model captures much of the trend, there is considerable noise.

# Fit an ARIMA model as an example
pre_intervention_data <- data$total_rides[data$service_date < as.Date("2020-03-01")]
arima_model <- auto.arima(pre_intervention_data)
residuals <- residuals(arima_model)

# Plot residuals
ggplot(data.frame(Date = data$service_date[data$service_date < as.Date("2020-03-01")], Residuals = residuals), aes(x = Date, y = Residuals)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "Residuals of Pre-Intervention Model", x = "Date", y = "Residuals") +
  theme_minimal()
## Don't know how to automatically pick scale for object of type <ts>. Defaulting
## to continuous.

# The ACF plot of the residuals indicates that most of the autocorrelations are within the significance bounds, except for the first lag. This suggests that the residuals are largely behaving like white noise, which is a good indication that the ARIMA model has captured most of the structure in the data.

# ACF of residuals
acf(residuals)

# Plot the PACF of residuals
pacf(residuals, main = "PACF of Residuals")

monthly_summary <- data %>%
  mutate(year = format(service_date, "%Y"),  # Extract year
         month = format(service_date, "%B")) %>%  # Extract full month name
  group_by(year, month) %>%
  summarise(
    monthly_bus = sum(bus, na.rm = TRUE),
    monthly_rail = sum(rail_boardings, na.rm = TRUE),
    monthly_total = sum(total_rides, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"  # Drop grouping for easier manipulation later
  )
# Filter data for January across all years
january_data <- monthly_summary %>%
  filter(month == "January")

  geom_bar(aes(y = monthly_bus, fill = "Bus"), stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  geom_bar(aes(y = monthly_rail, fill = "Rail"), stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "January Transportation Boardings Across Years",
       x = "Year",

## Analysis report {CausalImpact}
## 
## 
## During the post-intervention period, the response variable had an average value of approx. 603.32K. In the absence of an intervention, we would have expected an average response of 1362.48K. The 95% interval of this counterfactual prediction is [42.11K, 3251.48K]. Subtracting this prediction from the observed response yields an estimate of the causal effect the intervention had on the response variable. This effect is -759.16K with a 95% interval of [-2648.15K, 561.21K]. For a discussion of the significance of this effect, see below.
## 
## Summing up the individual data points during the post-intervention period (which can only sometimes be meaningfully interpreted), the response variable had an overall value of 874.21M. Had the intervention not taken place, we would have expected a sum of 1974.23M. The 95% interval of this prediction is [61.02M, 4711.39M].
## 
## The above results are given in terms of absolute numbers. In relative terms, the response variable showed an increase of +25%. The 95% interval of this percentage is [-82%, +87%].
## 
## This means that, although the intervention appears to have caused a positive effect, this effect is not statistically significant when considering the entire post-intervention period as a whole. Individual days or shorter stretches within the intervention period may of course still have had a significant effect, as indicated whenever the lower limit of the impact time series (lower plot) was above zero. The apparent effect could be the result of random fluctuations that are unrelated to the intervention. This is often the case when the intervention period is very long and includes much of the time when the effect has already worn off. It can also be the case when the intervention period is too short to distinguish the signal from the noise. Finally, failing to find a significant effect can happen when there are not enough control variables or when these variables do not correlate well with the response variable during the learning period.
## 
## The probability of obtaining this effect by chance is p = 0.222. This means the effect may be spurious and would generally not be considered statistically significant.

data_weekly_rides <- data %>%

  summarise(weekly_total_rides = sum(total_rides, na.rm = TRUE))
weekly_zoo_total <- zoo(data_weekly_rides$weekly_total_rides, order.by = data_weekly_rides$week)
overall_impact_weekly <- CausalImpact(weekly_zoo_total, pre.covid, post.covid, model.args = list(nseasons = 7, season.duration = 24))

## Warning in window.default(x, ...): Incompatible methods ("-.yearmon", "Ops.ts")
## for "-"

## Warning in window.default(x, ...): Incompatible methods ("-.yearmon", "Ops.ts")

arima <- auto.arima(ts_data_pre_covid,seasonal = TRUE,lambda = "auto")
arima
## Series: ts_data_pre_covid 
## ARIMA(2,1,0)(2,1,2)[12] 
## Box Cox transformation: lambda= 0.1931188 
## 
## Coefficients:
##           ar1      ar2    sar1     sar2     sma1    sma2
##       -0.6265  -0.2426  0.5620  -0.3262  -1.3558  0.4614

## 
## sigma^2 = 0.5805:  log likelihood = -256.78
## AIC=527.55   AICc=528.09   BIC=551.21
checkresiduals(arima)

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from ARIMA(2,1,0)(2,1,2)[12]
## Q* = 30.024, df = 18, p-value = 0.03722
## 
## Model df: 6.   Total lags used: 24
forecast_values <- forecast(arima, h = length(ts_data_post_covid))

# Extract the forecasted values
forecasted <- forecast_values$mean
rmse <- sqrt(mean((ts_data_post_covid - forecasted)^2))
mape <- mean(abs((ts_data_post_covid - forecasted) / ts_data_post_covid)) * 100

print(paste("RMSE:", round(rmse, 2)))
## [1] "RMSE: 9067485.35"
print(paste("MAPE:", round(mape, 2)))
## [1] "MAPE: 88.71"
